data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current code uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all elements satisfy a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Check a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Should contain an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure shows *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*
- **Add message parameters** — when `IsTrue` is unavoidable, the string arg explains *what* failed
- **`Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count)`** — better than `IsTrue(count > 0)` if you don't know the exact count

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify collection contains a specific item (uses .Equals)
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// Verify all items are of a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// No nulls in the collection
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// No duplicates
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);

// Exact match (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Same items regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer the most specific assertion available — it gives the best diagnostics on failure.
